      "secnum": "Deep Dive 12",
      "h": "Connecting Causes and Early Conflicts",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This checkpoint reviews key causes and early events of the Texas War of Independence to reinforce understanding before moving to later topics.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; history.com; guides.loc.gov. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>What political changes in Mexico contributed to the Texas Revolution?</li><li>How did social and economic factors influence Texan settlers?</li><li>Why were early battles like Gonzales important?</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Recall Mexico’s shift to centralism and the Battle of Gonzales as examples.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Answer the questions and reflect on how these factors interconnect.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Separating causes and events instead of seeing their connections.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; history.com; guides.loc.gov <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p>"
