      "h": "Military and Symbolic Dimensions of the Alamo",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The Siege of the Alamo was a critical early battle where a small Texan force held out against a larger Mexican army. Though the defenders were ultimately defeated, their sacrifice galvanized support for the revolution.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; thc.texas.gov; history.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Alamo was a mission turned fortress in San Antonio</li><li>Mexican forces led by Santa Anna besieged it for 13 days</li><li>Texan defenders included Davy Crockett and William B. Travis</li><li>Alamo’s fall became a rallying cry for Texan independence</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>The phrase 'Remember the Alamo!' was used to inspire Texan troops at later battles, notably San Jacinto.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Describe why the Alamo was strategically significant despite its defeat.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Viewing the Alamo only as a military loss without recognizing its symbolic power.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; thc.texas.gov; history.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup></p>"
