    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">17</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Military Campaigns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Battle of San Jacinto: Decisive Victory</h2><ul><li>Fought on April 21, 1836 near present-day Houston</li><li>Sam Houston led Texan forces in surprise attack</li><li>Mexican army under Santa Anna defeated and captured</li><li>Victory secured Texan independence</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Battle of San Jacinto was the turning point of the Texas Revolution. A swift and unexpected Texan attack overwhelmed Mexican forces, leading to Santa Anna’s capture and effectively ending major hostilities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Santa Anna’s capture forced him to sign treaties recognizing Texas independence, though Mexico later repudiated them.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify key factors that contributed to the Texan victory at San Jacinto.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming the battle was prolonged or evenly matched rather than a quick, decisive engagement.</p></div></div>",
